<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-07-03T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-07-03T00:00:00-05:00" n="260" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d260">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">793.94/570½</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-07-03">
                                    <hi rend="italic">3 July, 1917</hi>
                                </date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: As I have just
                            indicated to you, over the telephone, I entirely approve of this. I hope
                            that you will re-read the latter portion of it, however, with a view to
                            making the idea of Japan’s <hi rend="underline">political</hi> influence
                            over China a little more prominent as the thing we have <hi rend="underline">not</hi> assented to in the sense she evidently has
                            in mind.</p>
                        <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Woodrow Wilson</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>